VI have all my life wondered what "mind-boggling" meant.
p4
aVAfter two days here, I declare myself boggled, and enormously impressed,
p5
aVand feel that you are one of the great hopes \u2014
p6
aVnot just for American achievement in science and technology,
p7
aVbut for the whole world.
p8
aVI've come, however, on a special mission on behalf of my constituency,
p9
aVwhich are the 10-to-the-18th-power \u2014 that's a million trillion \u2014
p10
aVinsects and other small creatures, and to make a plea for them.
p11
aVIf we were to wipe out insects alone, just that group alone, on this planet \u2014
p12
aVwhich we are trying hard to do \u2014
p13
aVthe rest of life and humanity with it would mostly disappear from the land.
p14
aVAnd within a few months.
p15
aVNow, how did I come to this particular position of advocacy?
p16
aa(lp17
VAs a little boy, and through my teenage years,
p18
aVI became increasingly fascinated by the diversity of life.
p19
aVI had a butterfly period, a snake period, a bird period, a fish period, a cave period
p20
aVand finally and definitively, an ant period.
p21
aVBy my college years, I was a devoted myrmecologist,
p22
aVa specialist on the biology of ants,
p23
aVbut my attention and research continued to make journeys
p24
aVacross the great variety of life on Earth in general \u2014
p25
aVincluding all that it means to us as a species, how little we understand it
p26
aVand how pressing a danger that our activities have created for it.
p27
aa(lp28
VOut of that broader study has emerged a concern and an ambition,
p29
aVcrystallized in the wish that I'm about to make to you.
p30
aVMy choice is the culmination of a lifetime commitment
p31
aVthat began with growing up on the Gulf Coast of Alabama, on the Florida peninsula.
p32
aVAs far back as I can remember, I was enchanted by the natural beauty of that region
p33
aVand the almost tropical exuberance of the plants and animals that grow there.
p34
aVOne day when I was only seven years old and fishing,
p35
aVI pulled a "pinfish," they're called, with sharp dorsal spines, up too hard and fast,
p36
aVand I blinded myself in one eye.
p37
aVI later discovered I was also hard of hearing,
p38
aVpossibly congenitally, in the upper registers.
p39
aVSo in planning to be a professional naturalist \u2014
p40
aVI never considered anything else in my entire life \u2014
p41
aVI found that I was lousy at bird watching and couldn't track frog calls either.
p42
aVSo I turned to the teeming small creatures
p43
aVthat can be held between the thumb and forefinger:
p44
aVthe little things that compose the foundation of our ecosystems,
p45
aVthe little things, as I like to say, who run the world.
p46
aVIn so doing, I reached a frontier of biology so strange, so rich,
p47
aVthat it seemed as though it exists on another planet.
p48
aVIn fact, we live on a mostly unexplored planet.
p49
aVThe great majority of organisms on Earth remain unknown to science.
p50
aa(lp51
VIn the last 30 years, thanks to explorations in remote parts of the world
p52
aVand advances in technology,
p53
aVbiologists have, for example, added a full one-third of the known frog and other amphibian species,
p54
aVto bring the current total to 5,400,
p55
aVand more continue to pour in.
p56
aVTwo new kinds of whales have been discovered, along with two new antelopes,
p57
aVdozens of monkey species and a new kind of elephant \u2014
p58
aVand even a distinct kind of gorilla.
p59
aVAt the extreme opposite end of the size scale, the class of marine bacteria,
p60
aVthe Prochlorococci \u2014 that will be on the final exam \u2014
p61
aValthough discovered only in 1988, are now recognized as likely the most abundant organisms on Earth,
p62
aVand moreover, responsible for a large part of the photosynthesis that occurs in the ocean.
p63
aVThese bacteria were not uncovered sooner
p64
aVbecause they are also among the smallest of all Earth's organisms \u2014
p65
aVso minute that they cannot be seen with conventional optical microscopy.
p66
aVYet life in the sea may depend on these tiny creatures.
p67
aa(lp68
VThese examples are just the first glimpse of our ignorance of life on this planet.
p69
aVConsider the fungi \u2014 including mushrooms, rusts, molds and many disease-causing organisms.
p70
aV60,000 species are known to science,
p71
aVbut more than 1.5 million have been estimated to exist.
p72
aVConsider the nematode roundworm, the most abundant of all animals.
p73
aVFour out of five animals on Earth are nematode worms \u2014
p74
aVif all solid materials except nematode worms were to be eliminated,
p75
aVyou could still see the ghostly outline of most of it in nematode worms.
p76
aVAbout 16,000 species of nematode worms
p77
aVhave been discovered and diagnosed by scientists;
p78
aVthere could be hundreds of thousands of them, even millions, still unknown.
p79
aVThis vast domain of hidden biodiversity is increased still further
p80
aVby the dark matter of the biological world of bacteria,
p81
aVwhich within just the last several years
p82
aVstill were known from only about 6,000 species of bacteria worldwide.
p83
aVBut that number of bacteria species can be found in one gram of soil,
p84
aVjust a little handful of soil, in the 10 billion bacteria that would be there.
p85
aVIt's been estimated that a single ton of soil \u2014 fertile soil \u2014
p86
aVcontains approximately four million species of bacteria, all unknown.
p87
aa(lp88
VSo the question is: what are they all doing?
p89
aVThe fact is, we don't know.
p90
aVWe are living on a planet with a lot of activities, with reference to our living environment,
p91
aVdone by faith and guess alone.
p92
aVOur lives depend upon these creatures.
p93
aVTo take an example close to home: there are over 500 species of bacteria now known \u2014
p94
aVfriendly bacteria \u2014 living symbiotically in your mouth and throat
p95
aVprobably necessary to your health for holding off pathogenic bacteria.
p96
aa(lp97
VAt this point I think we have a little impressionistic film
p98
aVthat was made especially for this occasion.
p99
aVAnd I'd like to show it.
